Problem

Nearly all fish contain some trace of mercury. For most people, this is not a serious health concern, but higher levels of mercury can harm the developing nervous systems of fetuses or young children and its effects when consumed can be cumulative. The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) advise women who may become pregnant, pregnant women, nursing mothers, and young children to avoid some types of fish and eat others that are known to be lower in mercury. The EPA has guidelines about how much is considered safe to eat. Commercial fish is regularly tested, but wild-caught fish is harder to regulate. However, officials periodically sample local sources to assess the current level of risk from fish caught there.

Weekly fish servings Screening value (g/g) Chart category
0 > 0.46 Avoid
1 0.46 Good
2 0.23 Good
3 0.15 Best

The dataset FishMercury contains data for a sample of one frequently-consumed species of fish caught in a local lake. Mercury measurements are in parts per million (1 ppm = 1 g/g).

  1. Compute a bootstrap 95% percentile interval to estimate the true mean level of mercury for this species of fish in the sampled lake. Do not include any plots in this section.
merc <- fishdata$Mercury

N        <- 10^4
bootmean <- numeric(N)

for (i in 1:N){
  bootsample <- sample(merc, length(merc), replace = TRUE)
  bootmean[i] <- mean(bootsample)
}

quantile(bootmean, c(0.025, 0.975))
     2.5%     97.5% 
0.1125000 0.3071342
  1. Assess your bootstrap sampling distribution of \(\bar{x}\) for normality using a density plot, an ECDF plot, and a quantile-quantile plot. Include red reference curves for the theoretical normal distribution.
ggplot(NULL, aes(x = bootmean)) + 
  geom_density() +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean(bootmean), sd(bootmean)), color = "red")

ggplot(NULL, aes(x = bootmean)) + 
  stat_ecdf() +
  stat_function(fun = pnorm, args = list(mean(bootmean), sd(bootmean)), color = "red")

ggplot(NULL, aes(sample = bootmean)) + 
  stat_qq() + stat_qq_line(color = "red")

  1. Create an ordered factor variable called safety that categorizes fish in the sample as Best, Good, or Avoid. Then create a barplot to display that variable. Include an informative title and axis labels.
fishdata <- fishdata %>% 
  mutate(safety = factor(case_when(Mercury <= 0.15 ~ "Best",
                                   Mercury <= 0.46 & Mercury > 0.15 ~ "Good",
                                   Mercury > 0.46 ~ "Avoid"),
                         levels = c("Best", "Good", "Avoid")
  ))
ggplot(fishdata, aes(x = safety)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue", color = "gray") +
  labs(title = "Mercury Levels in Sampled Fish", x = "EPA Safety Category", y = "Number of Fish")

  1. Compute a bootstrap 95% percentile interval to estimate the true proportion of this species of fish that fall into the best category. Do not include any plots in this section.
safecat <- fishdata$safety

N        <- 10^4
bootprop <- numeric(N)

for (i in 1:N){
  bootsample <- sample(safecat, length(safecat), replace = TRUE)
  bootprop[i] <- mean(bootsample == "Best")
}

quantile(bootprop, c(0.025, 0.975))
     2.5%     97.5% 
0.4333333 0.7666667
